    <div class="inner">
        <div class="col-md-9 contribution content-container">



<p class="">If the right hon. Gentleman is suggesting it is very unfair for an individual to place his money on deposit at one-half per cent. interest and so pays less Income Tax than he would by placing his money where he got a better yield and so paid moreâ€”that is all the right hon. Gentleman is saying comes toâ€”I am sorry we are discussing it at an early hour of the morning, because I am sure he is showing difficulty in following the arguments advanced. He failed also to follow the arguments advanced by my hon. Friend. I know I am putting an intricate argument to follow, but I am doing my best and I hope I am succeeding in trying to put a difficult and important argument on this Clause<p></p> My argument is that whereas this Clause will apply to the perfectly ordinary commercial transactions entered into by a company without thought in its mind of tax avoidance or tax reduction, entered into for ordinary normal business purposes, but if that transaction entered into only with that object has the result of tax avoidance or tax reductionâ€”the fortuitous result, the result not contemplated but actually following, which was not by any means the intention with which it was entered intoâ€”then, I think I am right in saying, it will be deemed to be the purpose and held to be the purpose, in the light of those authorities I have referred to, even though the Special Commissioners might come to the definite <span id="1928" class="column-number" data-column-number="1928"></span> conclusion that there was no intention of avoiding or reducing tax.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
                        <a href="#contribution-5637209c-1d1c-4f52-9d5f-f4d8e0f30ef4" rel="popover" class="link-to-contribution link-to-contribution-mobile link-text" title="Share this contribution" data-placement="top"
                           data-hop-url-shorten-url="/UrlShortener/ShorternUrl"
