<p class="">We are pleased to have had the two contributions from the benches opposite. But at the conclusion of what I am sure hon. Members opposite will agree has been a very good tempered all-night Sitting, I am sorry that the hon. Member for Bilston (Mr. Nally), who has now apparently assumed very much more responsibility in the party opposite, should have been the first to strike a jarring note. But I think we must be grateful to him, despite the fact that some of his remarks were, I thought, unnecessarily offensive.<p></p> At the same time, I think that he put his finger upon the weakness of this Clause more effectively than have some of my hon. Friends, because after speaking of two or three instances of superannuation funds being established which had the consequences laid down in the Clause, he brought to his feet the hon. Member for Bath (Mr. Pitman) who, with great frankness, told the Committee that his own firm had such a scheme, whereupon the hon. Member for Bilston went on to say that he need not worry, and that he was all right.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
